            <fr:title text="Image factorisation">Image factorisation</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In <fr:link href="jms-00M6.xml" title="Lecture 18: surjections, injections, choice, and enumerability" addr="jms-00M6" type="local">Lecture 18</fr:link> we learned about <fr:link href="jms-00MN.xml" title="Injective functions" addr="jms-00MN" type="local">injective</fr:link> and <fr:link href="jms-00MF.xml" title="Surjective functions" addr="jms-00MF" type="local">surjective</fr:link> functions. In this section, we will see that <fr:em>any</fr:em> function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> can be factored as the composition of a surjection followed by an injection.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>6</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7687</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-016D</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-016D.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Image of a function">Image of a function</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> be an arbitrary function. The <fr:em><fr:strong>image</fr:strong></fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> in defined to be the subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Im}(f)\subseteq  B]]></fr:tex> spanned by the values of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
                <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \mathrm {Im}(f) = {\mathopen {}\left \{f(a)\,\middle \vert \,a\in  A\right \}\mathclose {}}
]]></fr:tex>
                <fr:p>We may at times write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m_f\colon  \mathrm {Im}(f)\hookrightarrow  B]]></fr:tex> for the subset inclusion, which is an <fr:link href="jms-00MO.xml" title="Injection" addr="jms-00MO" type="local">injective function</fr:link>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> also restricts to a function onto its image. In particular, we have:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
   e_f&\colon  A\to  \mathrm {Im}(f)\\
   e_f(x) &= f(x)
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>In fact, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e_f]]></fr:tex> is a surjection. To see that this is the case, we fix an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  \mathrm {Im}(f)]]></fr:tex> and we must find an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(a)=b]]></fr:tex>. But by definition of <fr:link href="jms-016D.xml" title="Image of a function" addr="jms-016D" type="local">images</fr:link>, we know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> is of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(a)]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> so we are done.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Furthermore, function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> is equal to the composite <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m_f\circ  e_f]]></fr:tex> as can be quickly seen: given <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex> we compute <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m_f(e_f(a)) = m_f(f(a)) = f(a)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
